<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-853-620  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 853 620.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Systems News  Nov 6 1989 n442 p14(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Language barriers trip up IBM; English software solutions don'tnecessarily translate overseas. (News)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Sperling, Ed.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>IBM's systems integration solutions, which can be duplicated andplugged into any business in a specific industry, encounterproblems overseas.andP;  IBM divisions that produce the software arelocated in the United States, and they write the software inEnglish.andP;  However, outside of the United Kingdom, few customerswant software that requires an understanding of English.andP;  Systemsintegration projects outside the United States tend to be laborintensive, and finding qualified people is difficult.andP;  Accordingto John Mignosa, IBM's acting director of systems integration forEurope, the Middle East and Africa, a solution is to subcontractwith vendors for expertise.andP;  The labor shortage has not hinderedIBM from dominating the systems integration marketplace: LondonIBM leads with about 17 percent of the commercial systemsintegration business in Europe, worth $187 million annually.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   International Business Machines Corp. (products).andO;Ticker:    IBM.andO;Topic:     Software PublishersComputer Systems IntegratorsSoftware EngineeringIntegrated Office SystemsForeign Languages.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>